-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - April 25
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Thu Apr 24, 2014 09:26PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, April 25 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  - Two senior executives at companies in the China Resources [CHRESR.UL] group were detained immediately after the state-run conglomerate's former chairman, Song Lin, was placed under investigation for corruption, sources familiar with the matter have revealed. (http://link.reuters.com/vyp78v) - Top Beijing officials slammed Occupy Central as an "illegal" movement that "damages the prosperity and stability of Hong Kong". (http://link.reuters.com/xyp78v) - The Communications Authority has stopped processing Hong Kong Television Network's <1137.HK> proposal to change the transmission standard for its mobile television service after the station took the dispute to court. (http://link.reuters.com/qaq78v)  THE STANDARD - Mainlanders are plotting a dirty revenge after a growing row over peeing in the street. Netizens even suggested that mainlanders should stink out Hong Kong during the coming Golden Week by getting their children to pee and poo wherever they like. (http://link.reuters.com/caq78v) - China, especially Shanghai, has the largest amount of shopping area under construction in the world, a survey by international property consultants CBRE has found. Shanghai took the lead by having 3.3 million square metres under construction as of January 31, 2014. (http://link.reuters.com/kaq78v) - The Philippine government has offered about HK$26 million ($3.35 million) as an "additional token of solidarity" to survivors and families of the eight Manila bus hostage victims in Hong Kong, with slain tour guide Masa Tse Ting-chunn's family getting about HK$1.5 million. (http://link.reuters.com/naq78v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  - China's top developer Vanke <000002.SZ> is scheduled to list its shares in Hong Kong by way of introduction without raising any capital, with the trading debut expected on June 19, according to a company disclosure on the Hong Kong bourse.  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  - The Link Real Estate Investment Trust <0823.HK>, which owns 182 commercial properties in Hong Kong, has appointed a surveying firm to sell 10 assets, according to market sources.